  "prompt": "Can I get infected with an STD from getting oral sex without protection?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to get infected with a sexually transmitted disease (STD) from receiving or giving oral sex without protection. Some STDs that can be transmitted through oral sex include:\n\n1. **Chlamydia**: Can infect the throat if exposed during oral sex.\n2. **Gonorrhea**: Can infect the throat and cause symptoms like a sore throat or be asymptomatic.\n3. **Herpes**: Herpes simplex virus (HSV) can be transmitted through oral contact, leading to oral or genital herpes.\n4. **Human papillomavirus (HPV)**: Certain strains of HPV can be transmitted through oral sex, potentially leading to oral cancers.\n5. **Syphilis**: Can be transmitted via oral sex if there is contact with a syphilitic sore.\n6. **HIV**: Although less common, HIV transmission can occur through oral sex, especially if there are cuts or sores in the mouth.\n\nUsing protection such as condoms and dental dams can reduce the risk of transmission of STDs during oral sex. Regular screenings and open communication with sexual partners about STI status are also important for sexual health.",
